post_text: The Oregon Behavioral Health Support Line is a free and confidential resource for all Oregonians who are looking for emotional support. Call 1-800-923-HELP (4357). You do not need to be in mental health crisis to call this line. If you need or want help beyond what the line can provide, you will be connected to those services. This can include community-based services such as housing, food assistance or clinical services. Certified interpreters are also available for those who speak a language other than English. Through this number, you can also connect with Lines for Life (linesforlife.org), a suicide prevention organization with specific resources for youth, military personnel and their families, and those affected by substance abuse problems.

post_text:
Looking for this year's school supply list? Stop looking, because it does not exist. We know times are stressful with COVID so we used our donations from Amazon to purchase the following for each student:
1) Earbuds with microphone for online learning
2) Neck buff (for when we return to onsite hybrid instruction)

In addition, each student will have a Chromebook checked out for his/her/their use. A mouse is available for Kinder and first grade students and students with special needs for whom operating the mousepad on the Chromebook is challenging.

Also, basic supplies (pencils, pens, crayons, paper, etc.) will be on meal buses. If you need a supply, just ask at meal delivery. If projects require additional supplies, they'll be sent home on buses as well.

Attention incoming kindergarten families: McNary Heights will be hosting kindergarten jumpstart classes this August. These classes are designed for students entering kindergarten this coming school year. Students in this two-week, 1⁄2 day summer program will learn listening, learning, and behavioral skills. They will become familiar with the school and routines, allowing for a much smoother start to the school year. Breakfast and lunch will be provided.

Completed applications can be turned in at the District Office, 1001 6th St. You may also contact us at 541-922-6500 if you would like an application mailed to your home. All applications are due by July 17, 2020.

shared_text:
Umatilla School District
June 1 at 9:21 PM ·

Thanks to the amazing flexibility of the City of Umatilla, Umatilla Police Department and the staff, we have updated GRADUATION plans. June 4th is our last day for students of 2020 and we'll celebrate in style by honoring our graduates AND enjoying an end of year party with fireworks over the river. Please join us online to watch graduation, along the parade route for celebration and from a distance for the fireworks. Thank you to ALL who work together to support each other. We are #UmatillaStrong and we are so thankful for our community!

June 4th, 2020
6:30 Drive Up Graduation (watch online at https://www.nfhsnetwork.com/schools/umatilla-high-school-umatilla-or)
7:30 Parade (Thank you, Umatila Police, route attached)
9:15 Fireworks (Thank you, City of Umatilla)

post_text: If you see a member of our maintenance and grounds crew, please help us thank them! They worked all afternoon yesterday to best prepare for the potential flooding from the river. After spending all week restoring the fields, the stakes were high and the river was rising quickly. Fortunately, their dedication was only surpassed by their skills. Our fields have survived another rising river and we are so thankful! As a reminder- please continue to stay off the fields and track, work will continue for at least another month.

Still feeling a little lost in Distance Learning? Remember, the website has many resources too. From mental health supports to how-to guides and phone numbers for help, you have a team to back you up. Just keep doing your best and remember that we understand that each situation is unique. We're here to work with you and support you.

Desde apoyo de salud mental hasta guías prácticas y números de teléfono para obtener ayuda, tiene un equipo que lo respalda. Simplemente sigue haciendo tu mejor esfuerzo y recuerda que entendemos que cada situación es única. Estamos aquí para trabajar con usted y apoyarlo.
https://umatilla.k12.or.us/supplemental-learning-resources-during-school-closure

post_text:
Distance Learning Update Video
Summary: You are all doing a GREAT job! We asked you to do your best and your best is simply amazing. Some are logging in once/week and doing all they can and that’s great. Some are logging in for every live session each day and that’s great. Some are doing paper packets and that’s great. Nearly ALL are participating and we couldn’t be prouder of our students and families! You are truly
#UmatillaStrong

Video de actualización de aprendizaje a distancia Resumen: ¡Todos están haciendo un GRAN trabajo! Le pedimos que haga lo mejor que pueda y lo mejor de usted es simplemente increíble. Algunos inician sesión una vez por semana y hacen todo lo que pueden y eso es genial. Algunos inician sesión en cada sesión en vivo todos los días y eso es genial. Algunos están haciendo paquetes de papel y eso es genial. ¡Casi TODOS están participando y no podríamos estar más orgullosos de nuestros estudiantes y familias! Eres verdaderamente
#UmatillaStrong

post_text: Governor Brown just announced on-site school closure for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. Distance learning for all students is now required. Superintendent Sipe will meet virtually with Seniors today at 3 pm (link sent to Seniors via email). She will do a Facebook Live for parents and families at 6 pm this evening. Further information is arriving via letters that will be mailed home tomorrow. We will post those letters here as well as soon as translation is complete.

shared_text:
OSU Extension, Umatilla County is at OSU Hermiston Agricultural Research and Extension Center.
March 25 at 1:57 PM · Hermiston, OR ·

Welcome to the Weekly Wednesday Food Hero Recipe Challenge! This week's challenge is open from March 25th until March 31st at 11:59 pm. You must reside in Umatilla or Morrow County to be eligible for the weekly prize drawing.

This week’s recipe is Food Hero Favorite Pancakes (with or without eggs); the recipe links are below:

https://www.foodhero.org/recipes/favorite-pancakes-eggs

https://www.foodhero.org/recipes/favorite-pancakes-without-eggs

Prepare this recipe at home and post a picture in the comments section or leave a comment sharing one thing you learned by preparing the recipe. Feel free to try one of the suggested variations posted in the recipe.

A random winner will be chosen to receive the brand new Food Hero Cookbook!! We will share the winner’s name in the comments section and send a private message through Facebook to obtain mailing information. Enjoy!

Food Hero
Moore Family Center for Whole Grain Foods, Nutrition & Preventive Health
Umatilla-Morrow Head Start, Inc.
Oregon Wheat

We are getting many questions regarding the Governor’s restrictions on gatherings above 25 people. We did clarify with the Oregon Department of Education today and they confirmed that the plan at this time is for students to return April 1st; however, that decision will be re-evaluated over the next week. We appreciate your patience as we all work together to move forward positively. We will post updates just as quickly as we are able.

Estamos recibiendo muchas preguntas con respecto a las restricciones de la Gobernadora en reuniones de más de 25 personas. Aclaramos hoy con el Departamento de Educación de Oregon y confirmaron que el plan en este momento es que los estudiantes regresen el 1 de Abril; sin embargo, esa decisión será reevaluada durante la próxima semana. Agradecemos su paciencia mientras todos trabajamos juntos para avanzar positivamente. Publicaremos actualizaciones tan rápido como podamos.

post_text: Information on COVID-19
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
February 28 at 4:21 PM ·

We know many of you are concerned about novel coronavirus (COVID-19) and are wondering what you can do to protect yourself and your family. While the risk of getting COVID-19 is currently low in Oregon, here are a few easy steps you can take:

-- Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol.
-- Cover your coughs and sneezes with a tissue and then throw the tissue in the trash.
-- Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
-- Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands.
-- Clean and disinfect surfaces that are often touched.
-- Take care of your overall health. Staying current on your vaccinations, including the flu vaccine, eating well and exercising all help your body stay resilient.
text:
Information on COVID-19

Oregon Health Authority
February 28 at 4:21 PM ·

We know many of you are concerned about novel coronavirus (COVID-19) and are wondering what you can do to protect yourself and your family. While the risk of getting COVID-19 is currently low in Oregon, here are a few easy steps you can take:

-- Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol.
-- Cover your coughs and sneezes with a tissue and then throw the tissue in the trash.
-- Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
-- Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands.
-- Clean and disinfect surfaces that are often touched.
-- Take care of your overall health. Staying current on your vaccinations, including the flu vaccine, eating well and exercising all help your body stay resilient.

post_text: Thank you for the thoughts and concerns regarding the Athletic Complex. We will not know the final impact of the damage until the water fully recedes. We’ll work with the Corps of Engineers this week to develop the plan for rebuilding our beautiful facility. Thank you for avoiding the area, please continue to do so. Even with the water levels dropping, it’s not a safe area at this time. As we feel sadness for the state of the fields, our thoughts go out to those who’ve lost much more. We’re thankful to be a part of a community, and region, that supports each other during times of challenge. We look forward to soon celebrating with you all during times of joy when the Complex is restored.

We are excited to announce a new offering for Umatilla students this year. We have teamed up with Family Health Associates to offer a Wellness Program for all students K-12. This program has three components:
• Well Child and Adolescent Well Visits (including sports physical)
• Vaccinations
• Acute Care (ear aches, sore throats, etc.)

To learn more, and to sign up for services, please visit this link: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdzFtN6xgEeKR9kF4eTeqDna5o2GjkFiAvrsP6mdyCfp2NV3A/viewform

We look forward to supporting healthy learners together!

Nos complace anunciar una nueva oferta para los estudiantes de Umatilla este año. Nos hemos asociado con Family Health Associates (FHA) para ofrecer un programa de bienestar para todos los estudiantes de K-12. Este programa tiene tres componentes:
• Visitas de bienestar para niños y adolescentes (incluido el físico deportivo)
• Vacunas
• Cuidado agudo (dolor de oídos, dolor de garganta, etc.)

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScLXr33WQERStQovbXSp5RTiyF-gMfEHyJGbcFTvxw4VO-AxA/viewform

Have your kids grown out of their formal wear? Donate it to the Umatilla School District! We will be holding a dance open to the community and your donations can give a child a night they will never forget.
We will be accepting all sizes for students k-8. Please wash the clothing before donating, clothing must be free of pet hair and smoke-free due to health reasons. If you are unable to, please put the clothing in a plastic bag with a note. Please take the clothing to McNary Heights Elementary. If you are in need of clothes, you can pick up the formal wear starting September 19 through the 17th at McNary Heights Elementary School.

Dance will take place Sunday, September 29, 2019. Stay tuned for more details.

shared_text:
InterMountain Education Service District
September 4, 2019 at 3:42 PM ·

The IMESD will provide free hearing screenings to public elementary school students at area schools this fall in Morrow, Umatilla and Union counties.

Students to be screened include kindergarten, first and third grade students, new students to a district and parent/teacher/principal referrals of students in other grades.

Screenings began September 3 and continue through the middle of November.

Parents who DO NOT want their child to be screened should notify their child’s school as soon as possible.

Scam Alert: We have now heard from multiple people that there is a person going door to door offering tutoring services on behalf of the Umatilla School District. This is not true. We do not authorize tutors on our behalf outside of school facilities.

Scam Alert: We have now heard from multiple people that there is a person going door to door offering tutoring services on behalf of the Umatilla School District. This is not true. We do not authorize tutors on our behalf outside of school facilities.

Alerta de estafa: Hemos escuchado de varias personas que hay una persona que va de puerta en puerta ofreciendo servicios de tutoría en nombre del Distrito Escolar de Umatilla. Esto no es verdad. No autorizamos tutores en nuestro nombre fuera de las instalaciones escolares.

post_text: Thank you, Umatilla Police Department! This week, they organized a drill to help us better prepare for emergencies. We were able to practice our emergency response system by working through a scenario with representatives from Oregon State Police, Morrow County Sherriff's Office, Umatilla Fire, Hermiston Fire and Ambulance, and the City of Umatilla Public Works. Nationally renowned school safety expert, Dr. Mary Schoenfeld was also on site to help us think through our planning and improve our response. We are incredibly grateful for the UPD, and the partner agencies and Dr. Schoenfeld, for helping us do all we can prepare for emergencies.

Nationally renowned school safety expert, Dr. Mary Schoenfeld was also on site to help us think through our planning and improve our response. We are incredibly grateful for the UPD, and the partner agencies and Dr. Schoenfeld, for helping us do all we can prepare for emergencies.

Umatilla School District has job opportunities. If you are interested in any of the openings, drop off your resume and letter of interest at the Umatilla School District office on 1001 6th St. in Umatilla. If you have any questions about any of the openings, call Josy Chavez at 541-922-6508.

Openings:
Operational Assistant 30 hours/week
Child Nutrition Assistant - 31.5 hours
Child Nutrition Assistant - 15 hours/week
Educational Assistant - 36 hours/week
Educational Assistant - 30 hours/week
Middle School Media Assistant 30 hours/week
Attendance Secretary - (Bilingual preferred) 40 hours/week

Job listing and job descriptions: https://umatilla.k12.or.us/employment

We were super excited when the Umatilla School District asked us to join them at their summer feeding program this summer! See you there!

We're working with the Oregon Energy Trust to reduce energy use in all buildings to save energy and cut costs. Recently, we had to count EVERY single light in our system. Take a guess as to how many lights we have! The person closest to exact (without going over) wins this awesome prize basket. We're accepting guesses on this form (linked here) through noon on Friday, June 14th, 2019. Happy guessing! https://forms.gle/KgbQQrLqGnm8Ash96

Thank you! The Umatilla community once again stepped up for students. We needed 300 drivers to earn $9,000 from our awesome partners at Tom Denchel Ford and we had 311. One IMPORTANT note- if you drove, please be sure to complete the survey in your email (if you did the online registration). We need the survey complete to claim the funds. Thank you!

¡Gracias! La comunidad de Umatilla una vez más demostró su apoyo para los estudiantes. Necesitábamos 300 conductores para ganar $9,000 de nuestros increíbles socios en Tom Denchel Ford y tuvimos 311. Una nota IMPORTANTE: si condujo, asegúrese de completar la encuesta en su correo electrónico (si hizo el registro en línea). Necesitamos la encuesta completa para reclamar los fondos. ¡Gracias!

post_text:
We are excited to begin dual language programs at McNary Heights this fall, starting with incoming Kindergartners. Parents can choose an English only classroom environment or a 50/50 split of English and Spanish instruction. To learn more about how this model works, check out the article from the East Oregonian

Estamos muy contentos de comenzar los programas de lenguaje dual en McNary Heights este otoño, comenzando con los estudiantes de Kinder entrantes. Los padres pueden elegir un entorno de salon solo en Inglés o una división 50/50 de instrucción en Inglés y Español. Para obtener más información sobre cómo funciona este modelo, consulte el artículo de East Oregonian

https://www.eastoregonian.com/news/local/umatilla-s-new-bilingual-program-aims-to-elevate-both-language/article_e30d10da-782a-11e9-aef8-af761e567ac8.html and watch this video: https://youtu.be/i-TMa8ZObl4
